This movie reminded me of The Hunger Games. The only difference is that The Hunger Games actually had a closing ending to each movie. And once they secured the budget for all the sequels they were able to make an ending like this movie did. This movie went ahead of themselves and ended the movie with the start of a revolution which sadly we will never get to see. All movies should have a Beginning, Middle, and END! This movie only had a Beginning and Middle, NO END. Movies are only allowed to have these types of endings when they have a budget secured for all the sequels. What do the adults in the movie assume will happen to all of the 'kids' when the adults can no longer contain them due to their old age?  Nothing about this movie makes sense, and it was a total waste of time.  I mean, could they have drilled the "You're special and Adults are Bad" any more than they did in this movie?  Seriously.  History will, hopefully, forget this filth.

Title: The Darkest Minds | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
For such a terrible and half-baked attempt of a film like this, I will admit it. This is a decent trailer. But there are questions.
1: Why are they showing(1:32 to 1:35)the SCENE were the main character(Ruby) forms the rebellion with the other kids? Even more embarrassing since that this is the VERY. LAST. SCENE before the credits start? And are just they just showing off their already pointless sequel hook?
2: How do we finally get to see Ruby "turning into Thanos'(I know that Thanos in NO SHAPE OR FORM appears in the film, but the effect looks ALMOST IDENTICAL. Just replace Thanos' dust with identical waves and there you go.)dust" in front of another main character(Liam) so quickly in the trailer(1:47)? Especially when it takes (around)90 MINUTES of the 100 minute film to see it happening in the final film?
3: HOW WERE THEY ABLE TO TAKE AN INCREDIBLY UNINTERESTING FILM AND MAKE INTO AN INTERESTING TRAILER? THAT'S QUITE AN ACCOMPLISHMENT, IF YOU CAN ASK ME!
I was surprised that this trailer got a VERY good amount of views(18 million!). Especially considering how badly it did at the box office(and with critics!).

Title: The Darkest Minds | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
When your 3rd last and last scenes of your movie are in your trailer, you have a bad trailer

When the climactic attack - not just climactic battle, the climactic attack - is in your trailer, you have a bad trailer

In fact, two entire fight sequences have their climactic attack in this trailer

Overall, the trailer clearly ignored the suspense of the movie and instead went for the raw power moments which meant all the good stuff was spoiled and you didn't think it was anything other than a dumb action flick...

I'm thinking of possible trailer designs.  I'm thinking start with the escape moment, focus on her mind controlling the guard and Cate's "Oh my God", and then set the scene of how it all started (girl at start dying, no kids, fear of survivors, concentration camps, violence at the camps) then build up all the threats that you face in the world after escaping and play up how everyone wants something and the distrust element.  Don't show anything from them reaching ED0 onwards (maybe a shot of reds throwing fireballs for the list of threats) - just build up to it and you could possibly hint with the "I can show you how to control your powers" towards the end.

Comment:
I hated this effin movie. It clearly reminded me of why I hate most writers. Great concept but characters all WASTED! 

Seems like the only decent character in the entire movie that was always ready to do what it takes was Zu. The little girl!

... and at every turn we see our lovely boring cast holding her back.

...another thing that burned me was this "Girl Power" CRAP! 

Just one scene prior she (Ruby) couldn't even get her thoughts together and didn't even know how to use her random ability. 
NO TRAINING WHATSOEVER! (SPOILER) Final showdown, she's controlling an army?! GTFOH!!!

Reminds me of the reviews i read about "The Last Jedi" nonsense...STILL REFUSE TO WATCH THAT ONE!!!

No issues with Ladies kicking butt... in fact, I think its HOT... but EARN YOUR KEEP!

This movie gets a 3/10 from me. It has some awesome potential, but suffered because of poor/dull storytelling and terrible character development.

Comment:
*This is just my opinion ,if someone actually reads this thanks (: and sorry for the long comment.*
Some people in the comments say that this was a copy of Hunger games,and they have a point because all of the books /movies that are based of them like The Maze Runner ,this and many more are all about stories that happen in a dystopic society,meaning the opposite of an utopic society,where everything is perfect,so basically the worst case scenario. 
 In my opinion the plots are interesting and the acting is mediocre(not always)  ,but at one point they simply become predictable and dull since all of the books and movies are not identical BUT all have the same structure.(Some of the books are really good as well as some movies).
I personally belive that filmmakers are very aware of all this,but instead of trying to approach a different concept beacuse it risks to be a commercial failure ,they will probably keep making these kind of movies for some time since the majority of the public enjoys them .
I think this movie was alright ,but not amazing.
 *Thanks again to anyone that took the time to read this and also if you a have a different opinion feel free to reply to my comment ,but please do it in an apropriate way I do not want to argue with anyone (:*

I.. have problems with this. I'm very happy that a movie adaptation is happening, but a lot is untrue.

-Liam should have a southern accent. and I'm sure we all pictured him more blonde, as he was described in the books

-zu is supposed to have close to no hair. I think they could've put the actress in a wig to create the illusion of it atleast

-no reds were part of the first book. they were only talked about.

-ruby. touchy subject. I think it's cool that more black representation is in Hollywood. it's a great step forward for how casting goes. but, her hair had been discribed as straight/tangled and her eyes green. I seriously doubt any author would describe curly-kinky hair as "tangled". and since she was taken as a child I will assume that wigs were not a part of life, nor were they mentioned. I say all this about her hair because I have yet to meet or know of a black person born with straight hair. it's just traits of their race, like how asian people will usually have dark eyes/hair. I hope I don't come off as "anti-black" or anything. my whole problem about this is that the director took it to herself to decide Ruby's race which is contradicting to what the books told us. sidenote: her name. Ruby Elizabeth Daly. Daly is of  Irish origins. thought I'd mention this.

-the van! justice should be delivered for Black Betty. she is a "mom van"!

-that scene with an amphitheater/arena ish look. never mentioned in the first book at all. also don't know why all those kids had their color painted on themselves. where did they come from? don't know. it's untrue.

-I get the suspicion that the plot has been reformed in some places and can't say I'm liking that too much

Comment: From what I understand, people think this looks generic and then automatically assume it‚Äôll be bad.  But why?  Sure, superpowers aren‚Äôt the most original or exciting thing anymore and it appears to play out some classic YA tropes, but that‚Äôs not a bad thing.  Their target is young adults so making the protagonists their age only makes sense, so that‚Äôs why they‚Äôre all kids and teens.  If that bothers you then you‚Äôre not their target audience and that won‚Äôt affect them one way or another.  Furthermore, please understand that tropes are reoccurring ideas in entertainment because they became popular.  Only when they are overused and become a tool rather than an idea does it become a cliche, so having precedent tropes does not automatically make it bad.  Now as someone who only found out this is based on a book series, I‚Äôm still highly intrigued.  I enjoy super powered plots (especially when that doesn‚Äôt automatically translate into being a superhero) and will probably watch this.  I know it‚Äôs a lot to ask, but please stop saying something will be garbage just because it follows a YA format and has powers (and that doesn‚Äôt make it an X-Men rip-off either).

*Blue*  is for those can  move things with their minds
*Green*  is for those who are highly intelligent.

Title: The Darkest Minds | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I love a lot of things about this, but they did change certain things from the book starting with black betty, but I don't mind the change/s if it/they served a purpose. I love how they kept in the detail of Chubs holding Liam's legs so he doesn't fall out or how Zu silently pointed and then the bullet hit the screen. However, this trailer doesn't show Ruby like the badass, sarcastic girl she was in the books and it shows a lot of red action. Don't get me wrong. This trailer and cast is everything I could hope for, but personally I'm still waiting for the scene where Ruby slaps Liam after the chase or something that shows the book more(like an adventure road trip with the white noise interfering and then how the characters get closer and how Ruby is insecure about her Orange powers and then growing stronger e.t.c). These are just my personal opinions so feel free to disagree, but I still have high hopes for this movie and nothing can be perfect. Also this may remind certain people of the x-men series, but I assure you that this is an original story with a different plot and storyline and the only thing remotely similar between the two is that it's about kid's that have power.
